'''SMS {{lang|de|Stettin}}''' ("His Majesty's Ship {{lang|de|Stettin}}"){{efn|"SMS" stands for "{{lang|de|[[Seiner Majestät Schiff]]}}", or "His Majesty's Ship".|group=Note}} was a {{sclass|Königsberg|cruiser (1905)|0}}  [[light cruiser]] of the {{lang|de|[[Kaiserliche Marine]]}} (Imperial Navy). She had three [[sister ship]]s: {{SMS|Königsberg|1905|2}}, {{SMS|Nürnberg|1906|2}}, and {{SMS|Stuttgart||2}}. Laid down at [[AG Vulcan Stettin]] shipyard in 1906, {{lang|de|Stettin}} was launched in March 1907 and commissioned into the [[High Seas Fleet]] seven months later in October. Like her sisters, {{lang|de|Stettin}} was armed with a main battery of ten {{convert|10.5|cm|abbr=on}} guns and a pair of {{convert|45|cm|abbr=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s, and was capable of a top speed in excess of {{convert|25|kn}}.

In 1912, {{lang|de|Stettin}} joined the [[battlecruiser]] {{SMS|Moltke||2}} and cruiser {{SMS|Bremen||2}} for a goodwill visit to the United States. After the outbreak of [[World War I]], {{lang|de|Stettin}} served in the reconnaissance forces of the German fleet. She saw heavy service for the first three years of the war, including at the [[Battle of Heligoland Bight (1914)|Battle of Heligoland Bight]] in August 1914 and the [[Battle of Jutland]] in May &ndash; June 1916, along with other smaller operations in the [[North Sea|North]] and [[Baltic Sea]]s. In 1917, she was withdrawn from frontline service and used as a [[training ship]] until the end of the war. In the aftermath of Germany's defeat, {{lang|de|Stettin}} was surrendered to the Allies and broke up for scrap in 1921&ndash;1923.

==Design==
{{main|Königsberg-class cruiser (1905)|l1=''Königsberg''-class cruiser}}

The {{lang|de|Königsberg}}-class ships were designed to serve both as fleet scouts in home waters and in [[German colonial empire|Germany's colonial empire]]. This was a result of budgetary constraints that prevented the {{lang|de|[[Kaiserliche Marine]]}} (Imperial Navy) from building more specialized cruisers suitable for both roles.{{sfn|Campbell & Sieche|pp=142, 157}} The {{lang|de|Königsberg}} class was an iterative development of the preceding {{sclass|Bremen|cruiser|4}}. All four members of the class were intended to be identical, but after the initial vessel was begun, the design staff incorporated lessons from the [[Russo-Japanese War]]. These included internal rearrangements and a lengthening of the [[hull (watercraft)|hull]]. ''Stettin'' was fitted with [[steam turbine]]s on an experimental basis; she was the second cruiser of the German fleet so equipped.{{sfn|Nottelmann|pp=110–114}}{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=188}}

[[File:Königsberg class cruiser diagrams Janes 1914.jpg|thumb|left|Plan and profile drawing of the {{lang|de|Königsberg}} class{{efn|The diagram mistakenly refers to the class as the {{lang|de|Stettin}} class and does not include {{lang|de|Königsberg}}}}]]

{{lang|de|Stettin}} was {{convert|115.3|m|sp=us}} [[length overall|long overall]] and had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|13.2|m|abbr=on}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|5.29|m|abbr=on}} forward. She [[displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{cvt|3480|t|lk=on}} normally and up to {{cvt|3822|MT}} at [[full load]]. The ship had a minimal [[superstructure]], which consisted of a small conning tower and [[bridge (nautical)|bridge]] structure. Her hull had a raised [[forecastle]] and [[quarterdeck]], along with a pronounced [[naval ram|ram bow]]. She was fitted with two pole [[mast (sailing)|masts]]. {{lang|de|Stettin}} had a crew of 14&nbsp;officers and 308&nbsp;enlisted men.{{sfn|Gröner|p=104}}

Her propulsion system consisted of a pair of [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons]] steam turbines that drove a pair of [[screw propeller]]s. Steam was provided by eleven coal-fired Marine-type [[water-tube boiler]]s that were vented through three [[funnel (ship)|funnels]]. The ship's propulsion system was rated to produce {{convert|13500|PS|lk=on}} for a top speed of {{convert|23|kn|lk=in}}, though she exceeded these figures in service. Normal coal storage amounted to {{cvt|400|t}}. At a more economical pace of {{convert|12|kn}}, the ship had a range of approximately {{convert|5750|nmi|lk=in}}.{{sfn|Gröner|p=104}}

The ship was armed with a [[main battery]] of ten [[10.5 cm SK L/40 naval gun|{{cvt|10.5|cm}} SK L/40 guns]] in single [[pivot gun|pedestal mounts]]. Two were placed side-by-side forward on the forecastle; six were located on the [[broadside (naval)|broadside]], three on either side; and two were side by side aft. The guns had a maximum elevation of 30&nbsp;degrees, which allowed them to engage targets out to {{convert|12700|m|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Campbell & Sieche|pp=140, 157}} They were supplied with 1,500 rounds of ammunition, amounting to 150 shells per gun. The ship was also equipped with eight [[5.2 cm SK L/55 naval gun|{{convert|5.2|cm|abbr=on|0}} SK guns]] with 4,000&nbsp;rounds of ammunition. She was also equipped with a pair of {{cvt|45|cm|1}} [[torpedo tube]]s with five [[torpedo]]es submerged in the hull on the broadside.{{sfn|Gröner|p=104}}

The ship was protected by a curved armor [[deck (ship)|deck]] that was {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} thick amidships. The deck sloped downward at the sides, with a thickness of {{cvt|45|mm}}, to provide protection against enemy fire. The [[conning tower]] sides were {{convert|100|mm|abbr=on}} thick. Her main battery guns were fitted with {{cvt|50|mm|0}} thick [[gun shield]]s.{{sfn|Gröner|p=104}}

==Service history==
[[File:SMS Bremen Stettin Moltke HamptonRoads 1912.jpg|thumb|{{lang|de|Stettin}} (center), with {{SMS|Bremen||2}} (L) and {{SMS|Moltke||2}} (R) in [[Hampton Roads]]]]

{{lang|de|Stettin}} was ordered under the contract name "{{lang|de|[[Ersatz]]}} {{SMS|Wacht||2}}"{{efn|German warships were ordered under provisional names. Additions to the fleet were given a single letter; ships intended to replace older or lost vessels were ordered as "{{lang|de|Ersatz}} (name of the ship to be replaced)".{{sfn|Dodson|pp=8–9}}}} on 20 December 1905. She was [[keel laying|laid down]] at the [[AG Vulcan]] shipyard in [[Stettin|her namesake city]] on 22 March 1906. She was [[ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 7 March 1907, and the mayor of Stettin gave a speech at the launching ceremony. [[Fitting-out]] work thereafter commenced, which was completed by September 1907. Because of her experimental turbines, the German Navy examined the ship thoroughly before accepting her. She was [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] into active service on 29 October to begin [[sea trials]]. Following her initial testing, she was assigned to the Scouting Unit on 20 January 1908, replacing the cruiser {{SMS|Frauenlob||2}}. At that time {{lang|de|[[Fregattenkapitän]]}} (FK—Frigate Captain) [[Friedrich Boedicker]] took command of the ship. In February, she and the rest of the scouting unit visited [[Vigo]], Spain, during a cruise with the [[High Seas Fleet]]. {{lang|de|Stettin}}{{'}}s normal peacetime routine of training exercises was interrupted from 17 June to 8 August, when she was ordered to escort {{lang|de|[[SMY Hohenzollern|Hohenzollern]]}}, the [[yacht]] of [[Kaiser Wilhelm II]]. During this period, the ships sailed to [[Stockholm]], Sweden, where the Swedish king, [[Gustav V]] visited {{lang|de|Stettin}}. Later in August, Boedicker was replaced by FK [[Curt von Rössing]].{{sfn|Gröner|pp=104–105}}{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|pp=187–188}}

In early 1909, civil unrest broke out in the [[Ottoman Empire]] against Christians living in the country. At the time, {{lang|de|Hohenzollern}} was cruising in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] with the cruiser {{SMS|Hamburg||2}} as the escort. {{lang|de|Hamburg}} was detached to intervene in southern [[Anatolia]] in the Ottoman Empire, and {{lang|de|Stettin}} was sent to replace her as the escort for {{lang|de|Hohenzollern}}. On 9 April, she departed [[Kiel]] in company with the light cruiser {{SMS|Lübeck||2}}, which was to support {{lang|de|Hamburg}} in operations off the coast of Anatolia. The ships arrived in [[Corfu]], an island off [[Greece]], on 1 May. While the ships were in [[Pula|Pola]], [[Austria-Hungary]], on 15 May, {{lang|de|Stettin}} received orders to return to Germany. She reached Kiel on 26 May. In October, FK [[Wilhelm Höpfner]] relieved Rössing as the ship's captain. {{lang|de|Stettin}} once again served as the escort for {{lang|de|Hohenzollern}} in 1910, from 7 to 30 July. This year, the ships cruised in Scandinavian waters. The ship's commander rotated again in September, with FK [[Johannes Hartog]] taking command. The year 1911 passed uneventfully for {{lang|de|Stettin}}, beyond the normal peacetime routine of training exercises and fleet maneuvers. In October, FK [[Wilhelm von Krosigk]] became the ship's next captain.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|pp=187–188}}

In March 1912, {{lang|de|Stettin}} was assigned to the East American Cruiser Division, which also included the [[battlecruiser]] {{SMS|Moltke||2}} and the light cruiser {{SMS|Bremen||2}}, and was commanded by {{lang|de|[[Konteradmiral]]}} (''KAdm''—Rear Admiral) [[Hubert von Rebeur-Paschwitz]]. The ships were sent to make a goodwill cruise to the United States; {{lang|de|Moltke}} was the only German [[capital ship]] to ever visit the US. On 11 May 1912 the ships left Kiel and arrived off [[Hampton Roads]], [[Virginia]], on 30 May. There, they met the US Atlantic Fleet and were greeted by then-President [[William Howard Taft]] aboard the presidential yacht {{USS|Mayflower|PY-1|6}}. After touring the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] for two weeks, they returned to Germany. On the way back, they stopped in Vigo from 22 to 26 June, before continuing on to Kiel, arriving there three days later. {{lang|de|Stettin}} thereafter returned to the reconnaissance unit.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=188}}{{sfn|Staff 2006|p=15}}{{sfn|Hadley & Sarty|p=66}}

In July 1913, {{lang|de|Stettin}} was sent to [[Pillau]] for a ceremony for the dedication of a monument for [[Frederick William, the Great Elector]]. Later that year, she was involved in a minor collision with the [[steam ship]] {{SS|Cassandra}}, and {{lang|de|Stettin}} had one of her [[spotting top]]s torn off a mast. The ship took part in her last peacetime training exercise with the High Seas Fleet in November 1913. She was thereafter replaced in the reconnaissance unit by the new cruiser {{SMS|Rostock||2}}, and on 4 February 1914, {{lang|de|Stettin}} had her crew reduced. On 1 July, the ship was reactivated and received a full crew; she was now to join the [[U-boat]] force as a [[submarine]] flotilla [[flagship]]. {{lang|de|Stettin}} became the flagship of II U-boat Flotilla. At that time, {{lang|de|[[Korvettenkapitän]]}} (Corvette Captain) [[Karl August Nerger]] took command of the ship; he served aboard the ship until March 1916.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|pp=187–188}} By that time, [[Archduke Franz Ferdinand]] of Austria-Hungary [[assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand|had been assassinated]], which sparked the [[July Crisis]] and led to the outbreak of [[World War I]] in late July, starting with the Austro-Hungarian declaration of war on Serbia on the 28th.{{sfn|Heyman|p=xix}}

===Actions in the North Sea===
{{lang|de|Stettin}} continued in her role as a U-boat flotilla flagship after the start of hostilities. On 6 August, she and the cruiser {{lang|de|Hamburg}} escorted a flotilla of U-boats into the North Sea in an attempt to draw out the British fleet, which could then be attacked by the U-boats. The force sailed about {{convert|100|nmi}} to the northwest of [[Helgoland]] and then returned to port without having encountered any British warships. They made a second sweep into the North Sea on 8 August, again without successfully locating any British ships.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=188}}{{sfn|Scheer|pp=34–35}}

====Battle of Helgoland Bight====
[[File:Battle of Heligoland Bight (1914) First Phase Map.png|thumb|Map showing the first phase of the battle, including {{lang|de|Stettin}}{{'}}s actions against the destroyers]]
{{main|Battle of Heligoland Bight (1914)}}

Some two weeks later, on 28 August, {{lang|de|Stettin}} was involved in the [[Battle of Heligoland Bight (1914)|Battle of Helgoland Bight]]. At the start of the engagement, {{lang|de|Stettin}}, {{lang|de|Frauenlob}}, and {{SMS|Hela||2}} stood in support of the line of torpedo boats patrolling the [[Helgoland Bight]]; {{lang|de|Stettin}} was at anchor to the northeast of Helgoland, and the other two ships were on either side. The German screen was under the command of Rear Admiral [[Franz von Hipper]], the commander of reconnaissance forces for the High Seas Fleet.{{sfn|Staff 2011|pp=4–5}} When the British first attacked the German torpedo boats, Hipper immediately dispatched {{lang|de|Stettin}} and {{lang|de|Frauenlob}}, and several other cruisers that were in distant support, to come to their aid. At 08:32, {{lang|de|Stettin}} received the report of German torpedo boats in contact with the British, and immediately weighed anchor and steamed off to support them. Twenty-six minutes later, she encountered the British destroyers and opened fire, at a range of {{convert|8.5|km|abbr=on}}. The attack forced the British ships to break off and turn back west. During the engagement, lookouts aboard {{lang|de|Stettin}} spotted a British cruiser in the distance, but it did not join the battle. By 9:10, the British had withdrawn out of range, and {{lang|de|Stettin}} fell back to get steam in all of her boilers. During this portion of the battle, the ship was hit once, on the starboard No. 4 gun, which killed two men and badly injured another. Her intervention prevented the British from sinking the torpedo boats {{SMS|V1||2}} and {{SMS|S13|1911|2}}.{{sfn|Staff 2011|pp=5–7}}

By 10:00, {{lang|de|Stettin}} had steam in all of her boilers, and was capable of her top speed. She therefore returned to the battle, and at 10:06, she encountered eight British destroyers and immediately attacked them, opening fire at 10:08. Several hits were observed in the British formation, which dispersed and fled. By 10:13, the visibility had decreased, and {{lang|de|Stettin}} could no longer see the fleeing destroyers, and so broke off the chase. The ship had been hit several times in return, without causing significant damage, but killing another two and wounding another four men. At around 13:40, {{lang|de|Stettin}} reached with the cruiser {{SMS|Ariadne||2}}, which was just coming under attack from several British battlecruisers. {{lang|de|Stettin}}{{'}}s crew could see the large muzzle flashes in the haze, which after having disabled {{lang|de|Ariadne}}, turned on {{lang|de|Stettin}} at 14:05. The haze saved the ship, which was able to escape after ten salvos missed her. At 14:20, she encountered {{SMS|Danzig|1905|2}}. The German battlecruisers {{SMS|Von der Tann||2}} and {{lang|de|Moltke}} reached the scene by 15:25, by which time the British had already disengaged and withdrawn. Hipper, in {{SMS|Seydlitz||2}}, followed closely behind, and ordered the light cruisers to fall back on his ships. After conducting a short reconnaissance further west, the Germans returned to port, arriving in [[Wilhelmshaven]] by 21:30.{{sfn|Staff 2011|pp=10–11, 21–22, 26}} In total, {{lang|de|Stettin}} had two men killed and nine wounded.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=188}}

====Fleet operations====
{{lang|de|Stettin}} was removed from her role as flotilla flagship on 25 November, and two days later, she was assigned to [[IV Scouting Group]], part of the reconnaissance screen for the battleships of the High Seas Fleet. She became the group flagship, under the command of {{lang|de|[[Kommodore]]}} (Commodore) [[Karl von Restorff]]. At that time, Restorff was also the commander of II&nbsp;Torpedo-boat Flotilla. In this new role, {{lang|de|Stettin}} became involved in the raids on the British coast that were carried out by the battlecruisers of [[I Scouting Group]].{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|pp=188–189}} The first that involved {{lang|de|Stettin}} began on 15 December, when I&nbsp;Scouting Group, led by Hipper, conducted a [[Raid on Scarborough, Hartlepool and Whitby|bombardment of Scarborough, Hartlepool, and Whitby]] on the English coast. The main body of the High Seas Fleet, commanded by Admiral [[Friedrich von Ingenohl]], stood by in distant support; {{lang|de|Stettin}} and two flotillas of torpedo boats screened the rear of the formation.{{sfn|Scheer|pp=68–69}} That evening, the German battle fleet of some twelve [[dreadnought]]s and eight [[pre-dreadnought]]s came to within {{convert|10|nmi|abbr=on}} of an isolated squadron of six British battleships. However, skirmishes between the rival screens in the darkness convinced Ingenohl that he was faced with the entire Grand Fleet. Under orders from Kaiser Wilhelm II to avoid risking the fleet unnecessarily, Ingenohl broke off the engagement and turned the battle fleet back toward Germany.{{sfn|Tarrant|pp=31–33}}

On 26 January 1915, Restorff's commands were divided; he retained control over II&nbsp;Torpedo-boat Flotilla and shifted his flag to the cruiser {{SMS|Kolberg||2}}, while ''KzS'' [[Georg Scheidt]] replaced him as commander of IV&nbsp;Scouting Group. Scheidt, who was promoted to {{lang|de|konteradmiral}} on 23 February, kept {{lang|de|Stettin}} as the group flagship. At that time, the unit consisted of {{lang|de|Stettin}} and the cruisers {{SMS|Stuttgart||2}}, {{lang|de|Danzig}}, {{SMS|Berlin||2}}, {{SMS|München||2}}, and {{lang|de|Frauenlob}}. {{lang|de|Stettin}} next went to sea for a fleet operation on 29 March, though IV&nbsp;Scouting Group was missing {{lang|de|Danzig}} and {{lang|de|Stettin}}; they were instead reinforced with {{lang|de|Hamburg}}. The operation concluded the following day, and failed to locate British vessels. On 11 April, {{lang|de|Stettin}}, {{lang|de|München}}, and {{lang|de|Frauenlob}} sortied to cover a patrol by the 2nd and 13th Torpedo-Half-Flotillas to the area south of [[Horns Rev]] to inspect fishing boats in the area. Two further fleet operations into the North Sea followed on 17–18 and 21–22 April, again without resulting in action with British forces.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=189}}

===Operations in the Baltic===
On 4 May 1915, IV Scouting Group, which by then consisted of {{lang|de|Stettin}}, {{lang|de|Stuttgart}}, {{lang|de|München}}, and {{lang|de|Danzig}}, and twenty-one torpedo boats was sent into the [[Baltic Sea]] to support a major operation against Russian positions at [[Liepāja|Libau]]. The operation was commanded by Rear Admiral Hopman, the commander of the reconnaissance forces in the Baltic. IV Scouting Group was tasked with screening to the north to prevent any Russian naval forces from moving out of the Gulf of Finland undetected, while several [[armored cruiser]]s and other warships bombarded the port. The ships of IV&nbsp;Scouting Group were ordered to patrol the line between [[Huvudskär]], [[Gotska Sandön]], and [[Saaremaa|Ösel]].{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=189}}{{sfn|Halpern|p=191}}

The Russians did attempt to intervene with a force of four cruisers: {{ship|Russian cruiser|Admiral Makarov||2}}, {{ship|Russian cruiser|Bayan|1907|2}}, {{ship|Russian cruiser|Oleg||2}}, and {{ship|Russian cruiser|Bogatyr||2}}. The Russian ships briefly engaged {{lang|de|München}}, and Scheidt recalled his other cruisers to join {{lang|de|Stettin}} to come to {{lang|de|München}}{{'}}s aid. The Russian forces were significantly stronger than the German light cruisers, but they believed more powerful German forces would intervene, and so they disengaged; indeed, when reports of the action arrived at German headquarters, the [[pre-dreadnought battleship]]s of [[IV Battle Squadron]] were detached to reinforce Scheidt's cruisers. Shortly after the bombardment, Libau was captured by the advancing German army, and {{lang|de|Stettin}} and the rest of IV Scouting Group were recalled to the High Seas Fleet, arriving back in the North Sea on 12 May.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=189}}{{sfn|Halpern|pp=191–193}}

===Return to the North Sea===
Soon after arriving back with the High Seas Fleet, {{lang|de|Stettin}} and the rest of IV&nbsp;Scouting Group sortied for another sweep into the North Sea on 17–18 May. Another attempt to catch British vessels in the southern North Sea took place on 29–30 May. Neither operation located hostile ships. The pace of operations slowed somewhat, and on 2 July, {{lang|de|Stettin}} again served in the covering force for a torpedo-boat patrol among the fishing ships south of Horns Rev. On 10 August, the fleet went to sea again, this time to cover the return of the [[auxiliary cruiser]] {{SMS|Meteor|1914|2}}, which was returning from a [[commerce raiding]] cruise. {{lang|de|Kommodore}} [[Ludwig von Reuter]] replaced Scheidt as the group commander on 3 September. {{lang|de|Stettin}} covered a minelaying operation off the [[Swarte Bank]] on 11–12 September. The final fleet operation of the war took place on 23–24 October in the direction of Horns Rev; like its predecessors, the ships did not encounter British vessels.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=189}}

The German fleet saw little activity over the winter of 1915–1916. The first major operation carried out by {{lang|de|Stettin}} and the rest of IV&nbsp;Scouting Group took place on 4 March, and it was a patrol to cover the return of the commerce raider {{SMS|Möwe|1914|2}}. The following day, the ships joined the main body of the High Seas Fleet for a sweep into the [[Hoofden]] that concluded on 7 March, again without result. {{lang|de|Stettin}} was [[dry dock]]ed for periodic maintenance from 8 to 25 March. Reuter temporarily left the ship on 28 March, as he was briefly transferred to command [[II Scouting Group]]. {{lang|de|Kommodore}} [[Paul Heinrich]], the commander of II&nbsp;Torpedo-boat Flotilla, was given command of IV&nbsp;Scouting Group in Reuter's absence, which lasted until 13 May, when Reuter returned to {{lang|de|Stettin}}. By this time, the unit consisted of {{lang|de|Stettin}}, {{lang|de|Stettin}}, {{lang|de|Frauenlob}}, and {{lang|de|München}}; in addition, {{lang|de|Hamburg}}, which was the flagship of the fleet's torpedo boat flotillas, was tactically assigned to IV&nbsp;Scouting Group. While Heinrich flew his flag aboard {{lang|de|Stettin}}, the ships took part in another fleet operation that resulted in the [[bombardment of Yarmouth and Lowestoft]] by the battlecruisers of I&nbsp;Scouting Group on 24–25 April.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=189}}

====Battle of Jutland====
[[File:Map of the Battle of Jutland, 1916.svg|thumb|Maps showing the maneuvers of the British (blue) and German (red) fleets on 30–31 May 1916]]
{{main|Battle of Jutland}}

In May 1916, the German fleet commander, Admiral [[Reinhard Scheer]], planned a major operation to cut off and destroy an isolated squadron of the British fleet. The operation resulted in the battle of Jutland on 31 May &ndash; 1 June 1916.{{sfn|Tarrant|p=61}} IV Scouting Group was tasked with screening for the main German battlefleet. As the German fleet approached the scene of the unfolding engagement between the British and German battlecruiser squadrons, {{lang|de|Stettin}} steamed ahead of the leading German battleship, {{SMS|König||2}}, with the rest of the Group dispersed to screen for submarines. {{lang|de|Stettin}} and IV Scouting Group were not heavily engaged during the early phases of the battle, since they were stationed close to the main body of the fleet and their guns could not hit targets at the long ranges at which the battle was primarily fought; through the daylight portion of the battle, they only managed to fire a few [[salvo]]es intermittently as British ships briefly came into range. But around 21:30, they encountered the British cruiser {{HMS|Falmouth|1910|6}}. {{lang|de|Stettin}} and {{lang|de|München}} briefly fired on the British ship, but poor visibility forced the ships to cease fire. Reuter turned his ships 90&nbsp;degrees away and disappeared in the haze.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=189}}{{sfn|Campbell|pp=35, 251–252}}

During the withdrawal from the battle on the night of 31 May at around 23:30, the battlecruisers {{lang|de|Moltke}} and {{lang|de|Seydlitz}} passed ahead of {{lang|de|Stettin}} too closely, forcing her to slow down. The rest of IV Scouting Group did not notice the reduction in speed, and so the ships became disorganized. Shortly thereafter, the British 2nd Light Cruiser Squadron came upon the German cruisers, which were joined by {{lang|de|Hamburg}}, {{SMS|Elbing||2}}, and {{lang|de|Rostock}}. A ferocious firefight at very close range ensued; {{lang|de|Stettin}} was hit twice early in the engagement and was set on fire. One of these hits knocked out one of her [[port and starboard|port]] 10.5&nbsp;cm guns. A shell fragment punctured the steam pipe for the ship's siren, and the escaping steam impaired visibility and forced the ship to abandon an attempt to launch torpedoes. In the melee, {{HMS|Southampton|1912|6}} was hit by approximately eighteen 10.5&nbsp;cm shells, including some from {{lang|de|Stettin}}. German observers aboard {{lang|de|Stettin}} reported seeing fires aboard the British cruiser. In the meantime, {{lang|de|Frauenlob}} was set on fire and sunk; as the German cruisers turned to avoid colliding with the sinking wreck, IV Scouting Group became dispersed. Only {{lang|de|München}} remained with {{lang|de|Stettin}}. The two ships accidentally attacked the German destroyers {{SMS|G11||2}}, ''V1'', and {{SMS|V3||2}} at 23:55.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=189}}{{sfn|Campbell|pp=276, 280–284, 390}}

By 04:00 on 1&nbsp;June, the German fleet had evaded the British fleet and reached [[Horns Reef]]; the Germans then returned to port.{{sfn|Tarrant|pp=246–247}} In the course of the battle, {{lang|de|Stettin}} had suffered eight men killed and another 28 wounded. She had fired a total of 81 rounds of ammunition from her 10.5&nbsp;cm guns.{{sfn|Campbell|pp=341, 360}}

===Subsequent operations===
After the battle, {{lang|de|Stettin}} was docked at the [[Reiherstieg Schiffswerfte & Maschinenfabrik]] shipyard in [[Hamburg]] for repairs that lasted from 7 to 22 June. She was then moved to the {{lang|de|[[Kaiserliche Werft Wilhelmshaven|Kaiserliche Werft]]}} (Imperial Shipyard) in Wilhelmshaven for additional work from 6 to 19 July. By the time repairs to the ships of IV&nbsp;Scouting Group were completed in July, the unit consisted of {{lang|de|Stettin}}, {{lang|de|Stuttgart}}, {{lang|de|Danzig}}, {{lang|de|Hamburg}}, {{lang|de|München}}, and {{lang|de|Berlin}}. From 18 to 20 August, the ships participated in a fleet operation into the southern North Sea, which resulted in the [[Action of 19 August 1916|action of 19 August]]. Reuter was transferred back to II&nbsp;Scouting Group on 11 September, and he was replaced by {{lang|de|Kommodore}} [[Karl Seiferling]]. Another fleet sortie took place on 18–20 October, as far as east of the [[Dogger Bank]]. During the operation, {{lang|de|München}} was torpedoed by a British submarine and had to be towed back to port by {{lang|de|Berlin}}. {{lang|de|Stettin}} evaded one torpedo but another hit the ship. The warhead failed to detonate, but the impact nevertheless dented the hull and tore some of the plating. On 3 December, {{lang|de|Stettin}} was replaced as the group flagship by the cruiser {{SMS|Stralsund||2}}.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|pp=189–190}}

{{lang|de|Stettin}} took part in a minelaying operation on 10 January 1917, which laid a defensive mine barrier between Helgoland and [[Norderney]]. For the rest of the year, the German fleet remained largely in port, and the cruisers of IV&nbsp;Scouting Group were largely confined to defensive patrols in the [[German Bight]] to protect the [[U-boat]] force as it departed from and returned to its bases in Germany. On 4 July, {{lang|de|Stettin}} went to the Baltic for training exercises; she was also used as a [[target ship]] during shooting practice. This period lasted until 10 November. She was detached from IV&nbsp;Scouting Group in August, and on 10 September, she became the flagship of the Commander of the Defenses of the Western Baltic Sea, ''KAdm'' [[Hermann Nordmann]]. She replaced the pre-dreadnought {{SMS|Deutschland|1904|2}} in that role. {{lang|de|Stettin}} departed for periodic maintenance in Wilhelmshaven on 8 December. By the time she returned to the Baltic on 17 February 1918, Nordmann's command had been merged with its counterpart for the central Baltic, and he became the Commander of the Defence of the Baltic, though he shifted his flag from {{lang|de|Stettin}} to {{lang|de|Kolberg}}.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=190}}

At that time, {{lang|de|Stettin}} was withdrawn from front line service and used as a [[training ship]] with the U-boat school. She was employed as a target ship for U-boat crews to practice torpedoing a moving target. There was some debate about converting the ship into a [[seaplane tender]], as had been done to her [[sister ship]] {{SMS|Stuttgart||2}} earlier that year, but the discussion came to nothing. Instead, she served briefly as the flagship for the Commander of Minesweeping and Clearing Force from 10 June to 20 July, at which point she was replaced by the cruiser {{SMS|Augsburg||2}}. {{lang|de|Stettin}} thereafter returned to the U-boat school, where she remained until the end of the war in November. During this period, on 25 September, Kaiser Wilhelm II visited the ship.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|pp=190, 212}}{{sfn|Campbell & Sieche|p=157}}

On 11 November, the [[Armistice with Germany]] went into effect, ending the fighting in World War I. Following Germany's defeat, {{lang|de|Stettin}} was decommissioned in Wilhelmshaven on 19 or 20 December in Kiel.{{efn|Records in the [[German Federal Archives]] give conflicting dates.{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=190}}|group=Note}}{{sfn|Hildebrand, Röhr, & Steinmetz|p=190}} She was specified among the list of vessels to be surrendered to the [[Allies of World War I|Allied powers]] as a [[war prize]] under the terms of the [[Treaty of Versailles]].{{sfn|Dodson & Cant|p=33}} She was accordingly stricken from the [[naval register]] on 5 November 1919. She left Germany in company with the cruiser {{lang|de|Danzig}} and thirteen torpedo boats between 9 and 11 September 1920 and arrived in [[Rosyth]], Great Britain, on 17 September,{{sfn|Dodson & Cant|p=45}} where {{lang|de|Stettin}} was surrendered to Great Britain under the transfer name "T". The terms of the Versailles treaty required that ex-German warships be dismantled or rendered unusable by specific dates; as the deadline for {{lang|de|Stettin}} (16 March 1922) rapidly approached, she was sold to shipbreakers in [[Copenhagen]] and dismantled for scrap by 1923.{{sfn|Gröner|p=105}}{{sfn|Dodson & Cant|p=55}}

