==Production==
===Development===
[[File:Thomas Stearns Eliot by Lady Ottoline Morrell (1934).jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Photograph of T.S. Eliot|The title of the film, ''Winter Kept Us Warm'', comes from [[T. S. Eliot]]'s ''[[The Waste Land]]''.]]

[[David Secter]], originally from [[Winnipeg]], was a 4th-year student at the [[University of Toronto]] when he made ''Winter Kept Us Warm'', his debut feature film.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=3}} His only prior film experience was the 8 minute short film ''Love with the Proper Guppy''{{sfn|Lack of Experience Helps|1965}} he made on a budget of [[Canadian dollar|CAD]]$31.88.{{sfn|Montreal Star|1966}} Having been a film reviewer for ''[[The Varsity (newspaper)|The Varsity]]'', he has stated that he was inspired by the [[French New Wave]]: "A lot of those New Wave guys had started out as critics, and I thought, 'Hey, if they can move from talking about movies to making movies, why can't I?{{'"}}{{sfn|Pevere|2011}}

The film was originally titled ''Doug and Peter'', but Secter renamed it to ''Winter Kept Us Warm'' which is another line from ''[[The Waste Land]]'' by [[T. S. Eliot]].{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=29}} When Secter selected the title he was unaware of rumours about Eliot's sexuality or theories about ''The Waste Land'' being a gay romance. He felt that the line properly captured how he wanted to portray connections.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=95}}

Toronto had an active gay community,{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=3}} with nine [[gay bar]]s in Toronto in 1964.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=11}} Other Canadian films in the 1960s, such as ''[[À tout prendre]]'', ''[[The Fox (1967 film)|The Fox]]'', and ''[[Deliver Us from Evil (1969 film)|Deliver Us from Evil]]'', dealt with queer subjects as well.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=19}} Secter noted that homosexuality was a "triple taboo" as it was a sin according to religion, a crime by the state, and labeled as a mental illness.{{sfn|Pedwell|2015}}

On 1 November 1964, a meeting was held in Eric Rump's room. Many of the attendees believing they were joining a filmmaking club and did not come to later meetings after being told that it was focused on Secter's film project. Ron B. Thomson, who attended the first meeting, became the film's executive producer. According to Thomson, attendance of the meetings fell to around 20, including actors, film crew, and hangers-on.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|pp=29-30}} Secter found most of the cast by placing a classified advertisement in the university's student newspaper ''The Varsity''.{{sfn|Hicklin|1964}} Secter went to the [[Toronto Metropolitan University|Ryerson Polytechnic Institute]]'s photography department to find technicians and found Robert Fresco and Ernest Meershoek, the directors of photography for the film.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=31}} The entire crew worked for free as volunteers.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|pp=3; 38}}

The fundraising goal for the film was $5,000. The Students' Administration Council offered $750, but Secter stated that this was offered as a loan and would require him to give up distribution rights. The council later gave him $500 with no other requirements. He received $800 from [[University College, Toronto]].{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=36}}{{sfn|No strings attached|1965|p=2}} The film received a $750 grant from the [[University of Toronto Students' Union]], along with permission to film several key scenes at [[Hart House (University of Toronto)|Hart House]].{{sfn|Hicklin|1964}} The [[Canada Council]], the [[Ontario Arts Council]], and the [[National Film Board of Canada]] declined to give grants.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=37}} The final cost of the film was $8,000 ({{Inflation|CA|8,000|1964|fmt=eq}}).{{sfn|The Varsity|1965|p=6}}{{sfn|Turner|1987|p=59}}

===Casting===
[[File:Lorne Michaels (1988 FOX press photo).jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Photograph of Lorne Michaels|[[Lorne Michaels]] was initially cast in the role of Nick, but withdrew from the project.]]

Although the film is considered English Canada's first gay film,{{sfn|Knegt|2020}} the cast of the film was not made aware of the film's queer subject matter.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=57}} There were no auditions for the film.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=32}} Secter noted that the actors were fine with nudity as it was not strange on campus; men still swam nude at Hart House at the time.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=85}}

The first two actors cast to play Doug withdrew from the project. Secter saw [[John Labow]] in a Hart House production of ''[[Look Back in Anger]]''. Labow was selected on 18 November and rehearsals with [[Henry Tarvainen]] started that afternoon.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|pp=33-34}}

Robert Gill, the artistic director of Hart House Theatre, suggested to [[Janet Amos]] that she become involved in ''Winter Kept Us Warm''. [[Joy Fielding|Joy Tepperman]] learned of the film from Amos, who was cast as a girlfriend, and asked Secter if she could also be cast as a girlfriend. A second girlfriend did not exist in the script at the point and Doug was initially envisioned as a [[Promiscuity|womanizer]]. Fielding convinced him to make the character and Secter had her involved in developing it.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=33}}

[[Lorne Michaels]] was initially cast as Nick, but withdrew from the project. He provided assistance with the script. Jack Messinger was selected to replace Michaels.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=32}} Messinger's leg broke during production and it was incorporated into the film.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=40}}

===Filming===
''Winter Kept Us Warm'' was the first feature film shot at the University of Toronto. There was difficulties with acquiring permission as there was no centralized system and Secter had to ask permission at every location he went to. A 5-page treatment outlining the story and listing the required locations was submitted to [[Douglas LePan]], but rejected the request on 30 October 1964, citing its [[Homoeroticism|homoerotic]] elements.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=34}}

Secter later stated that he was so inexperienced that he did not know until the first day of filming that the [[clapperboard]] was used to synch audio and was instead used to make sure everybody knew he was filming.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=68}} On 22 November, a scene of Doug and Peter meeting in the library was shot for use in gaining financial support. Filming started at 3{{Nbsp}}pm and was planned to end at midnight, but lasted until 7{{Nbsp}}am. The next scene, which features Doug and Peter interacting in a dining room, was shot on 8 December and featured over 100 extras.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=36}}

Filming started without a script as Secter was pressed for time. He needed to be a student to use university locations and would be graduating the next year. No complete script was made for the film. John Clute and Ian Porter, who appeared in the cast party scene, wrote dialogue for the film.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=35}}

Most of the shots in the film were done in a single take.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=40}} The scenes at the library were shot after it closed for the night and the scenes at the dining hall were filmed between mealtimes. [[Guerrilla filmmaking]] was used for the winter carnival scenes. The apartment of a cast member's sister was used for Sandra's house and the cast party took place in a basement flat rented by Secter.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=41}}

Secter obtained partially used film reels from other production companies as a way to cut costs.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=36}} Bob Crone, the founder of Toronto film lab and post-production facility Film House, agreed to let the production run up a debt. This was the first production that Film House was involved with.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=38}} {{Convert|1,200|ft|m}} of film negatives were lost and never found.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=40}}

===Editing===
On 27 April 1965, Secter received a letter from the Commonwealth Film Festival in [[Cardiff]], United Kingdom, requesting that ''Winter Kept Us Warm'' be submitted for consideration. He initially did not reply as the film was not finished, but the festival made and sent multiple phone calls and telegrams. The only portion of the film that had been edited was a 7-minute sample shown to prospective investors, so Secter sent them the sample. Their decision to include the film was confirmed on 16 July, much to the shock of Secter.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=44}}

Secter had wanted to edit the film himself, but had to change his plans after the film was confirmed for the Commonwealth Film Festival. A three hour [[rough cut]] was created by July. Michael Foytényi was brought onto the project at the recommendation of Secter's acting teacher John Hirsch. Foytényi, realizing that the project was too big for him to do on his own, brought on George Appleby. Appleby edited 35–40% of the film by himself according to Secter.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=44}}

When editing began, the ending for the film had not yet been determined. Secter considered having Doug reconcile with Bev, but instead chose to end the film with Doug reading ''The Waste Land'' alone in the library. Filming started again in July and ended on 21 August.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=45}}

===Music===
[[File:PaulHoffert (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Photograph of Paul Hoffert|[[Paul Hoffert]], a student at the [[University of Toronto]], was the composer for ''Winter Kept Us Warm''.]]

[[Paul Hoffert]], a University of Toronto science major, was the film's composer. He was a professional musician and did work for the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]. Hoffert worked for free, but requested a budget for professional musicians. The soundtrack consisted of Rob McConnell on the trombone, Moe Koffman on the flute, Eugene Amaro on the alto sax and flute, Ron Laurie on the cello, Ed Bickert on the guitar, Stan Zadak and Doug Willson on the acoustic double bass, and Ed Thigpen and Stan Perry on the drums.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=31}}

==Release==
Secter was unable to find funding to travel to Cardiff and instead travelled with Fresco on a charter flight to [[Edinburgh]] alongside a [[rugby union]].{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=47}}{{sfn|Times & Transcript|1965}} ''Winter Kept Us Warm'' premiered as the opening film of the Commonwealth Film Festival on 27 September 1965. As the film was on [[16 mm film]], a special apparatus had to be used due to the theatre normally only showing [[35 mm movie film|35 mm film]].{{sfn|Turner|1987|p=59}}{{sfn|Pevere|2011}}{{sfn|The Hamilton Spectator|1965}}

It was distributed in Canada by the Canadian Filmmakers' Distribution Centre.{{sfn|Turner|1987|p=59}} Secter initially sought to show the film at the New Yorker Theatre, but it declined his offer citing its poor sound quality. On 26 October 1965, he booked a two-week screening at the [[Royal Ontario Museum]]. Its run at the Royal Ontario Museum started on 6 December, which was the first time the cast saw the completed film. As Secter chose to self-distribute the film he was able to keep most of the profits and pay off the production costs. The [[Ontario Film Review Board]] gave the film a Restricted rating. It received a commercial release in January 1966, in Winnipeg and Toronto.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|pp=48-49}} By July 1966, the film earned $6,000 in Toronto.{{sfn|Calgary Herald|1966}} Specter received $500 for winning a special jury prize at the 4th Canada Film Festival.{{sfn|Edmonton Journal|1966}}

Secter sent a copy of the film to the NFB, hoping that it would agree to distribute the film. Lucille Bishop, the NFB's distribution agent, submitted the film to the [[1966 Cannes Film Festival]]'s [[Critics' Week]].{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=49}} ''Winter Kept Us Warm'' was the first English-Canadian film to be shown at the [[Cannes Film Festival]].{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=4}} The Canadian government paid for Secter's travel to Cannes.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=51}}

At the [[1984 Toronto International Film Festival|1984 Festival of Festivals]] the film was screened as part of Front & Centre, a special retrospective program of artistically and culturally significant films from throughout the history of Canadian cinema.{{sfn|Scott|1984}} [[TLA Video]] released the film on DVD in 2011.{{sfn|Hudson|2011}} In 2015, the film was screened at [[Buddies in Bad Times]] during Toronto's [[Pride Week (Toronto)|Pride Week]] as the centrepiece of a selection of LGBT-themed Canadian films, to mark the launch of Thomas Waugh's Queer Media Database project.{{sfn|Beeston|2015}}

==Reception==
''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s review of the film praised the cinematography of downtown Toronto, but noted that its stilted dialogue and inconsistent sound quality made it more suitable for film societies than theatres.{{sfn|Variety|1983}} [[Renata Adler]] criticized the cinematography as amateurish.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=66}}

The ''[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]''{{'}}s film review praised its background music and depiction of university life.{{sfn|The Hamilton Spectator|1965}} Frank Morriss gave the film a moderately favourable review in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' writing that Labow's want to have a good time and Tarvainen's desire to make good is interesting, but that the film loses direction when Tarvainen gains confidence and Labow's feelings run amok.{{sfn|Morriss|1965}} [[Robert Fulford (journalist)|Robert Fulford]], writing for the ''[[Toronto Star]]'', stated that it was "an interesting though uneven exercise", but that it was an encouraging sign for the Canadian film industry.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=73}}

[[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]], writing for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', praised the film for using a traditional narrative rather than psychedelic effects and [[cinéma vérité]] used by other young filmmakers.{{sfn|Thomas|1968}} Jacob Siskind, writing for ''[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]'', praised the acting as far better than other student productions.{{sfn|Siskind|1966}}

Writing about the film for ''[[The Body Politic (magazine)|The Body Politic]]'' in 1982, [[Thomas Waugh]] expressed concern about the fact that gay-themed films of its era rarely depicted positive same-sex relationships, but instead usually centred on love triangles involving a woman; while acknowledging that ''Winter Kept Us Warm'' reflected this trope, he complimented the film for portraying its women characters with greater integrity than usual for the genre.{{sfn|Waugh|1982}} [[Norman Wilner]] wrote that the film was "a breakthrough in its treatment of queer characters as fully dimensional human beings" in a release promoting a fall 2024 screening at the [[TIFF Lightbox]].{{sfn|Wilner|2024}} [[Joe Medjuck]] stated that the editing was crude, the acting was clumsy, and felt that the queer elements were not relevant to the plot.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|pp=65-67}}

