==Legacy==
[[File:David Cronenberg 2012-03-08.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Photograph of David Cronenberg|[[David Cronenberg]] credits ''Winter Kept Us Warm'' with inspiring him to launch his film career.]]

''Winter Kept Us Warm'' fell from public notice, with it being excluded from the ''Canadian Film Reader'' and ''50 Years of Queer Cinema'', and ''[[The Celluloid Closet (book)|The Celluloid Closet]]''. Waugh stated that homophobia was the result of its exclusion from Canada's national film history while Radu Davidescu noted that the subtlety of its queerness causes it to be ignored as a queer film.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|pp=89-90}} The limited distribution of ''Winter Kept Us Warm'' also harmed its visibility according to Waugh.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=92}}

Although not widely remembered among the general public, ''Winter Kept Us Warm'' is considered a major milestone in the Canadian film industry as one of the first Canadian films ever to attract international attention. Secter made a second film, ''[[The Offering (1966 film)|The Offering]]'', in 1966, one of the first Canadian films to depict an [[Miscegenation|interracial]] romance.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=65}}{{sfn|Knelman|2005}}{{sfn|CBC|2024}} [[David Cronenberg]], who was a student at the University of Toronto at the time, was amazed by the film and believed that he too could make films like Secter had.{{sfn|Rodley|1997|page=11}}{{sfn|Vatnsdal|p=19}}{{sfn|Gainey|2022}}

In the late 1980s Secter considered making a sequel to ''Winter Kept Us Warm'' titled ''Memory and Desire'', based on another line from ''The Waste Land''. The film would have been set in 1990, and followed the lives of the four main characters since the previous film. Peter and Sandra were married with a son while Doug and Bev were separated after having a daughter. Doug moves to California and has not seen his daughter in over 20 years. His daughter persuades him to return to Toronto for a class reunion and he meets Peter, Sandra, and Bev.{{sfn|Dupuis|2024|p=61}}

In the 1990s, Secter's nephew [[Joel Secter]] rented ''[[Feelin' Up|Getting Together]]'', not knowing that his uncle had directed films. Seeing David's name in the credits, Joel contacted his uncle to talk about his film career. Those discussions ultimately led to Joel's own debut as a filmmaker, the 2005 documentary ''[[The Best of Secter and the Rest of Secter]]''.{{sfn|Knelman|2005}}

In 2023, [[Telefilm Canada]] announced that ''Winter Kept Us Warm'' was one of 23 titles that would be digitally restored under its new Canadian Cinema Reignited program to preserve classic Canadian films.{{sfn|Mullen|2023}} The restored version premiered at the [[Inside Out Film and Video Festival]] in May 2024,{{sfn|Hertz|2024}} before being screened at various film festivals in 2025, including the [[International Film Festival of Ottawa]],{{sfn|International Film Festival of Ottawa}} [[BFI Flare]],{{sfn|Tabbara|2025}} and the [[Queer North Film Festival]].{{sfn|The Sudbury Star|2025}}

In 2024, Chris Dupuis published a book about the film as part of the [[McGill–Queen's University Press]] ''Queer Film Classics'' series.{{sfn|CBC|2024}}

