'''Liselott Margarete''' "'''Lisa'''" '''Kahn''' ({{née|'''Kupfer'''}}; July 15, 1921 – July 3, 2013) was a German-American poet and scholar of psychology and [[German studies]]. She studied at the [[University of Heidelberg]], where she obtained a PhD in psychology in 1953. She married the German-American scholar [[Robert Ludwig Kahn|Robert L. Kahn]] and emigrated to the United States, where she was a teacher at [[The Kinkaid School]] from 1964 to 1968 and professor of German at [[Texas Southern University]] from 1968 to 1990, serving as head of the foreign language department from 1988.

In her scholarly work, Kahn was concerned with the experience of German-speaking immigrants to the United States, among other topics. She especially studied American women writing in German and edited an anthology of related work. As a poet, immigration and the related ambiguous feelings towards the home country were among her themes. She was one of the most productive American poets writing in German and was described as the "foremost German Texan poet"{{sfn|Tolzmann|1986}} and a "prototypical example" of a German-American author.{{sfn|Glenn|1994}} Kahn received several awards and distinctions including the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]] in 1990.

==Life and career==
Kahn was born as Liselott Margarete Kupfer in [[Berlin]] on July 15, 1921, as daughter of a merchant. She attended school in [[Leipzig]], where she graduated with the [[Abitur]] in 1940. She then completed a {{ill|Pflichtjahr|de}} followed by two years of work in an aluminum foundry and two years of service with the [[German Red Cross]]. After [[World War II]], she worked as [[Language interpretation|interpreter]] for the legal division of the US [[Office of Military Government, United States|Office of Military Government]] in [[Württemberg-Baden]]. From 1948 to 1953 she studied psychology, German literature and English at the [[University of Heidelberg]].{{sfn|Klimt|2016}} She spent the academic year 1950/51 at the [[University of Washington]] sponsored by the [[Fulbright Program]].{{sfn|Niers|2013}} She obtained a PhD in psychology in 1953 from the University of Heidelberg,{{sfn|Klimt|2016}} with a 1952 thesis in social psychology{{sfn|Hoefert|1968|p=86}} entitled {{lang|de|Versuch einer Sozialcharakterologie der dichterischen Gestalten des Naturalismus}}, "Attempt of a social [[characterology]] of the poetic figures of [[naturalism (literature)|naturalism]]".{{sfn|Kupfer-Kahn|1952}}{{sfn|Psychologisches Institut}}

In 1951, she married Jewish German refugee [[Robert Ludwig Kahn|Robert L. Kahn]],{{sfn|Niers|2013}} also a poet and scholar of German studies. Robert Kahn had also lived in Leipzig in the 1930s, but they only met during her Fulbright year in the United States.{{sfn|Mieder|2004|p=59}} They had two children, including her son Peter.{{sfn|Röder|Strauss|2016|p=584}} Robert became a US citizen in 1956,{{sfn|Röder|Strauss|2016|p=584}} Lisa in 1958.{{sfn|Niers|2013}} The family moved to [[Houston]] in 1962,{{sfn|Niers|2013}} where Robert was professor of German at [[Rice University]] until his 1970 suicide,{{sfn|König|Wägenbaur|2011|p=877}} and Lisa taught German and French at [[The Kinkaid School]] in [[Piney Point Village, Texas|Piney Point Village]], from 1964 to 1968.{{sfn|Klimt|2016}} From 1968 she was a professor of German at [[Texas Southern University]].{{sfn|Niers|2013}}{{sfn|Mieder|2004|p=60}} She became head of the foreign language department in 1988 and retired in 1990.{{sfn|Rosenstein|Kreutz|1997|p=460}}

Lisa Kahn later married Herbert Finkelstein{{sfn|Kreuzer|1990|p=188}} and converted to Judaism in 1973.{{sfn|Niers|2013}}{{sfn|Röder|Strauss|2016|p=584}} She died in Houston on July 3, 2013.{{sfn|MLA|2014}}{{sfn|Kürschner|2014|p=1198}} Kahn was a member of [[PEN International|International PEN]] from 1982, of [[PEN America|American PEN]] from 1985 and of {{ill|Österreichischer PEN-Club|de|lt=PEN Austria}} from 1989.{{sfn|Mieder|2004|p=60}} She received various distinctions and awards, including the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]] in 1990{{sfn|Niers|2013}}{{sfn|Mieder|2004|p=60}} and was named {{lang|la|Poeta Laureata}} by the [[University of New Mexico]]{{sfn|Grimm|1998}} in 1993.{{sfn|Klimt|2016}} For her contributions to German in Texas, she received the German-Texan Heritage Society's {{lang|de|Ehrenstern}} award.{{sfn|Mieder|2004|p=60}} The Society for Contemporary American Literature in German's annual poetry prize, named after Robert L. Kahn from 1988 to 2013,{{sfn|TRANS-LIT2}} is now called the Lisa & Robert Kahn Prize for Poetry in German.{{sfn|SCALG}}

==Scholarship and poetry==
Lisa Kahn was interested in literature about the experience of German-speaking immigrants to the United States. She surveyed and collected writing in German by American women writers, noting that the use of the German language helped keep their identity intact.{{sfn|Kahn|1978a}} She edited a volume of related prose and poetry, {{lang|de|Reisegepäck Sprache}}, in 1979, that among other goals aimed to relieve the comparative lack of representation of women writers in literary anthologies.{{sfn|Duncan|1981}}{{sfn|Kahn|1979}} Reviewer Annelise Duncan from [[Trinity University (Texas)|Trinity University]] praised Kahn's "sensitivity and expertise".{{sfn|Duncan|1981}} Together with [[University of Cincinnati]] professor of German, Jerry Glenn, she produced an updated bilingual edition in 1983, ''In her mother's tongue''.{{sfn|Kahn|Glenn|1983}}{{sfn|Metzger|1987|p=200}} She also wrote about other authors including [[Ernst Jandl]], [[Günter Kunert]], [[Friederike Mayröcker]] and [[Kurt Tucholsky]].{{sfn|Mieder|2004|p=61}}

She wrote poems in English and German, and was one of the most productive German writing poets in the United States.{{sfn|Bauschinger|2001|p=233}} After her first husband's suicide, her main themes were suffering and death.{{sfn|Kreuzer|1990|p=188}} Starting in 1975 with {{lang|de|Klopfet an, so wird euch nicht aufgetan}},{{sfn|Niers|2013}} Kahn published her poetry and short prose in eighteen volumes.{{sfn|Mieder|2004|p=62}} In 1978, she edited {{lang|de|Tonlose Lieder}}{{sfn|Kahn|1978b}} ('Songs without sound'), a collection of poems by Robert, illustrated by her son Peter.{{sfn|Pabisch|1980}} The 1982 collection ''David am Komputer'' contained some poems made to look like computer programs and other plays on form. Reviewer Solveig Olsen called some of the poems "strong, direct, and classic in their simplicity."{{sfn|Olsen|1983}} Kahn's 1984 bilingual volume ''From my Texas Log Cabin'', contained texts about Texas and was also illustrated by Peter, and reviewer Glen E. Lich noted the effect of the "intertextual resonance of the facing translations".{{sfn|Lich|1985}} Reviewer Don Tolzmann noted Kahn's "unique perspective" and found the poems dealt "quite successfully with basic universal themes".{{sfn|Tolzmann|1986}} Linda Moehle-Vieregge found the German poems "remarkable" but characterized the direct translation of some German compound words into English (for example, {{lang|de|selbstgezimmert}} as "self-carpentered") as "irritating".{{sfn|Moehle-Vieregge|1986}} The 1986 collection ''Flußbettworte / Fluvial Discourse'' was described by reviewer Rita Terras as "exceptionally broad" in range, using a wide selection of types of poetry and geographical settings.{{sfn|Terras|1999}} Some of her poetry books included English texts and reflected on her experience with immigration and bilinguality.{{sfn|Niers|2013}} Her book {{lang|de|Kinderwinter}}, illustrated by her son, showed the tension of her mixed feelings towards Germany.{{sfn|Pabisch|1988}} The 1992 collection ''Atlantische Brücke'' portrays the experience of returning emigrants as a building of bridges.{{sfn|Bauschinger|2001|p=233}} Some of Kahn's poems also have Jewish themes or concern the Holocaust.{{sfn|Bauschinger|2001|p=233}}

Jerry Glenn described Kahn as "the prototypical example of an important author who is universally recognized as 'German-American'" in an article on the definition of German-American Literature.{{sfn|Glenn|1994}} Don Tolzmann called her "without question the foremost modern German Texan poet".{{sfn|Tolzmann|1986}}

